16. Name and explain the four types of Joins in MySQL.

Answer

Joins in MySQL are used to combine data from two or more tables based on a related column.

The four main types of Joins are:
• INNER JOIN
• LEFT JOIN
• RIGHT JOIN
• FULL JOIN

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. INNER JOIN

INNER JOIN returns only the matching records from both tables.

Syntax

SELECT columns
FROM table1
INNER JOIN table2
ON table1.column_name = table2.column_name;

Example

SELECT employees.name, departments.department_name
FROM employees
INNER JOIN departments
ON employees.department_id = departments.department_id;

Explanation
• Only employees with matching departments are displayed.

Real-Time Example

Employee Table

Employee_ID      Name      Department_ID
101              Rahul     1
102              Priya     2

Department Table

Department_ID      Department_Name
1                  HR
2                  IT

Output

Rahul      HR
Priya      IT

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2. LEFT JOIN

LEFT JOIN returns:
• All records from the left table
• Matching records from the right table

If no match exists, NULL values are returned.

Syntax

SELECT columns
FROM table1
LEFT JOIN table2
ON table1.column_name = table2.column_name;

Example

SELECT employees.name, departments.department_name
FROM employees
LEFT JOIN departments
ON employees.department_id = departments.department_id;

Explanation
• All employees are shown even if department data is missing.

Real-Time Example

Employee Table

Employee_ID      Name      Department_ID
101              Rahul     1
102              Priya     NULL

Department Table

Department_ID      Department_Name
1                  HR

Output

Rahul      HR
Priya      NULL

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

3. RIGHT JOIN

RIGHT JOIN returns:
• All records from the right table
• Matching records from the left table

If no match exists, NULL values are returned.

Syntax

SELECT columns
FROM table1
RIGHT JOIN table2
ON table1.column_name = table2.column_name;

Example

SELECT employees.name, departments.department_name
FROM employees
RIGHT JOIN departments
ON employees.department_id = departments.department_id;

Explanation
• All departments are displayed even if no employees exist.

Real-Time Example

Department Table

Department_ID      Department_Name
1                  HR
2                  IT
3                  Finance

Employee Table

Employee_ID      Name      Department_ID
101              Rahul     1

Output

Rahul      HR
NULL       IT
NULL       Finance

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

4. FULL JOIN

FULL JOIN returns:
• All matching records
• All non-matching records from both tables

MySQL does not directly support FULL JOIN.
It can be achieved using UNION.

Example

SELECT employees.name, departments.department_name
FROM employees
LEFT JOIN departments
ON employees.department_id = departments.department_id

UNION

SELECT employees.name, departments.department_name
FROM employees
RIGHT JOIN departments
ON employees.department_id = departments.department_id;

Explanation
• Combines results of LEFT JOIN and RIGHT JOIN.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Key Differences

INNER JOIN
• Returns only matching records

LEFT JOIN
• Returns all records from left table

RIGHT JOIN
• Returns all records from right table

FULL JOIN
• Returns all records from both tables

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Important Point

• Joins are widely used in relational databases.
• They help combine related data efficiently.
• INNER JOIN is the most commonly used Join in real-world applications.

